{{Infobox person | name = Abraham Golomb | birth_date = 1888 | birth_place = Lithuania | death_date = 1982 | death_place = Los Angeles | occupation = Yiddish educator and lyricist }}
'''Abraham Golomb''' (1888, [[Lithuania]] - 1982, [[Los Angeles]]; Yiddish אברהם יצחק גולומב) was a Yiddishist teacher and writer.<ref>{{Citation | title = Golomb, Abraham | year = 2007 | journal = Encyclopaedia Judaica | pages = 744 | last1 = Liptzin | first1 = Sol | last2 = Estraikh | first2 = Gennady}}</ref> He wrote many pedagogical articles and books, and also published, primarily in Yiddish, about his belief in the need for retaining Jewish distinctiveness in the [[Jewish diaspora|Diaspora]] and the centrality of Hebrew and Yiddish as the languages of the Jewish people.<ref name=Network>{{Citation |title=GOLOMB, Abraham. |url=http://www.cjhn.ca/permalink/177 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130615231638/http://www.cjhn.ca/permalink/177 |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2013-06-15 |author=Network, The Canadian Jewish Heritage |accessdate=2013-06-14 }}</ref> His work has not been widely translated into English.
Golomb was affiliated with the Psychology and Education section of [[YIVO]] in Vilna, under the direction of by [[Leibush Lehrer]],<ref>{{Citation | title = YIVO | url = http://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/judaica/ejud_0002_0021_0_21275.html | journal = Jewish Virtual Library | accessdate = 2013-06-14 }}</ref> and was also active in the Kultur-lige.<ref name=Kazovsky>{{Citation | title = Kultur-lige | url = http://www.yivoencyclopedia.org/printarticle.aspx?id=271 | author = Kazovsky, Hillel | journal = The YIVO Encyclopedia of Jews in Eastern Europe | accessdate = 2013-06-14 }}</ref> From 1921 to 1931, he was the director of the Vilna Teachers Seminary.<ref name=Geller2009>{{Citation | title = The twin weeklies – Wiadomości Literackie and Literarishe Bleter | url = http://icj.huji.ac.il/conference/papers/Aleksandra%20Geller.pdf | year = 2009 | author = Geller, Aleksandra | journal = Between Coexistence and Divorce 25 Years of Research on the History and Culture of Polish Jewry and Polish–Jewish Relations | accessdate = 2013-06-14 }}</ref>
After a living in Palestine from 1932 to 1938, Golomb emigrated to Winnipeg, Canada, where he became principal of the Peretz School. In 1944 he moved to Mexico City, where for 20 years he ran the Yiddish schools. Finally, in 1964 he and his wife Rivke Savich Golomb moved to Los Angeles, California.<ref name=Staropolsky-shwartz2009>{{Citation | title = Rivke Savich Golomb | url = http://jwa.org/encyclopedia/article/golomb-rivke-savich | year = 2009 | author = Staropolsky-shwartz, Frida | journal = Jewish Women: A Comprehensive Historical Encyclopedia | accessdate = 2013-06-14 }}</ref>
==Selected works== *''Ṿi fun a fish iz a frosh geṿorn: zikhroynes̀ fun mayn ḳindheyṭ''. (''How a fish became a frog: memories of my childhood'') Bialystok: Ferlag Ḳulṭur lige, 1921. *''Dos ershṭe mol in ṿald : zikhroynes̀ fun mayn ḳindheyṭ''. (''The first time in the forest: memories of my childhood'') Bialystok: Ferlag Ḳulṭur lige, 1921. *אייביקע וועגן פון אייביקן פאלק : עסייען / ''Eybiḳe ṿegn fun eybiḳn folḳ : eseyn'' (''Eternal ways of eternal people: essays''). Buenos Aires : Yoyvl-ḳomiṭeṭ, 1964. *צווישן תקופות / [פון] א. גאלאמב'' Tsṿishn tḳufes̀''. (''Between epochs''). Tel-Aviv: Y.L. Peretz, 1968.
